1 administration of justice, may remove the justice or judge from office or may censure or
2 otherwise discipline the justice or judge, or the Supreme Court of Maryland, after hearing
3 and upon a finding of disability which is or is likely to become permanent and which
4 seriously interferes with the performance of the justice’s or judge’s duties, may retire the
5 justice or judge from office.
6 (2) A justice or judge removed under this section, and the justice’s or
7 judge’s surviving spouse, shall have the rights and privileges accruing from the justice’s or
8 judge’s judicial service only to the extent prescribed by the order of removal.
9 (3) A justice or judge retired under this section shall have the rights and
10 privileges prescribed by law for other retired justices or judges.
11 (4) No justice of the Supreme Court of Maryland shall sit in judgment in
12 any hearing involving that justice’s own conduct.
13 (c) This section is alternative to, and cumulative with, the methods of retirement
14 and removal provided in Sections 3 and 4 of this Article, and in Section 26 of Article III of
15 this Constitution.
16 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the General Assembly
17 determines that the amendment to the Maryland Constitution proposed by Section 1 of this
18 Act affects multiple jurisdictions and that the provisions of Article XIV, § 1 of the Maryland
19 Constitution concerning local approval of constitutional amendments do not apply.
20 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the amendment to the
21 Maryland Constitution proposed by Section 1 of this Act shall be submitted to the qualified
22 voters of the State at the next general election to be held in November 2026 for adoption or
23 rejection in accordance with Article XIV of the Maryland Constitution. At that general
24 election, the vote on the proposed amendment to the Constitution shall be by ballot, and on
25 each ballot there shall be printed the words “For the Constitutional Amendment” and
26 “Against the Constitutional Amendment”, as now provided by law. Immediately after the
27 election, all returns shall be made to the Governor of the vote for and against the proposed
28 amendment, as directed by Article XIV of the Maryland Constitution, and further
29 proceedings had in accordance with Article XIV.

